<section xml:id="exploration-3">
  <title>Exploration 3, due February 15</title>
<handout xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="exam1-logic-problems">
    <title>Exploration 3, due February 15</title>
  <page>
    <title>List of Problems</title>
    <p>
        Make sure to familariaze yourself with the Exploration <xref ref="instructions" text="custom"> Instructions </xref> found on the home page.
      </p>

    <p>Consider the following problems from previous Exam 1 midterms.</p>

    <ol marker="(1)">
      <li>
        <p><strong>1(a)viii T/F (Fall ’25):</strong></p>
        <p>If <m>\vec b\in\mathrm{Span}\{\vec v_1,\vec v_2\}</m> and
        <m>\vec b\in\mathrm{Span}\{\vec v_2,\vec v_3\}</m>, then
        <m>\vec b\in\mathrm{Span}\{\vec v_1,\vec v_3\}</m>.</p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p><strong>1(a)vi T/F (Spring ’25):</strong></p>
        <p>If <m>\vec u</m> and <m>\vec v</m> are both solutions to an inhomogeneous
        system <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m>, then <m>\vec u+\vec v</m> is also a solution
        to <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m>.</p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p><strong>1(a)v T/F (Spring ’23):</strong></p>
        <p>If <m>A</m> is size <m>3\times 4</m> and none of the rows of <m>A</m>
        consist entirely of zeros, then <m>A</m> has 3 pivots.</p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p><strong>1(a)v T/F (Fall ’23):</strong></p>
        <p>If <m>\{\vec v_1,\vec v_2\}</m> is a linearly independent set, then
        <m>\mathrm{span}\{\vec v_1,\vec v_2\}=
          \mathrm{span}\{\vec v_1+\vec v_2,\;\vec v_1-\vec v_2\}</m>.</p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p><strong>1(a)i T/F – modified (Spring ’25):</strong></p>
        <p>If the system <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m> is inconsistent, then there is not a
        pivot in the last row of the REF of the coefficient matrix <m>A</m>.</p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p><strong>1(a)ii T/F (Spring ’24):</strong></p>
        <p>If the linear transformation <m>T(\vec x)=A\vec x</m> is one‑to‑one,
        then <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m> has a unique solution.</p>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <problem>
        <statement>
            <p>
      For each of the true/false problems above, complete tasks (i)–(ii) below.

    <ol marker="(i)">
      <li>
        <p>Write the problem and provide the answer.</p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>Do one example that illustrates whether the statement
        could be true or must be false. The example may be:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>an example showing the statement can be satisfied, or</li>
          <li>a counterexample showing the statement must be false.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          For instance, for problem (1) you would choose a matrix <m>A</m> and vectors
          <m>\vec u,\vec v,\vec b</m> so that <m>\vec u</m> and <m>\vec v</m>
          both satisfy <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m>, then check whether
          <m>\vec u+\vec v</m> also satisfies the equation.
        </p>

        <p>
          Say explicitly whether your example is a counterexample or not. <em>Note:</em> Your example does <strong>not</strong> need to be a counterexample
      even if the original statement is false—any example is acceptable.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
</problem>

  </page>

  <!-- ================= PAGE 4: New Problems 7–8 ================= -->
  <page>
    <title>Create New Problems</title>
    <problem>
    <statement>
        <p>
      Create two new problems (7) and (8). Each new problem should be a
      modification of <strong>one</strong> of the six original problems. For example,
      you may:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>change the premise or conclusion of an implication,</li>
      <li>switch “onto” with “one‑to‑one”,</li>
      <li>change “linearly independent” to “linearly dependent”,</li>
      <li>swap the order of the implication, or negate the if‑part or then‑part.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      After writing each new problem, repeat tasks (i)–(ii). Clearly state which
      original problem you modified.
    </p>
</statement>
</problem>

  </page>

